=== The Marriage Quest of Ōkuninushi === {{ill|Yachihoko|ja|八千矛神|qq=draft}}, another name for Ōkuninushi, sought to wed {{ill|Nunakawahime|ja|沼河比売|qq=draft}} of {{ill|Koshi Province|ja|高志国|qq=draft}}. He journeyed to her land, where they exchanged love poems. However, his actions enraged Suseribime, who became fiercely jealous. As he fled from Izumo to {{ill|Yamato Province|ja|Yamato Province|qq=draft}}, he sang a farewell song to Suseribime, who, in turn, responded with a song offering him a farewell cup. The two exchanged cups, signifying their continued connection, and it is said that they remain enshrined to this day.<ref>Tobe, pp. 93–99.</ref> == Analysis == * These tales are found in the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|qq=draft}} but not in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft}}. * The myths demonstrate parallels to initiation rites and worldwide mythological motifs, such as the hero's trials and resurrection. * The healing process involving {{ill|Kisagai-hime and Umugi-hime|ja|キサガイヒメ・ウムギヒメ|qq=draft}} resembles the use of [[:en:Anadara_broughtonii|ark shell]] powder mixed with [[:en:Meretrix_lusoria|clam]] juice for burn treatment, which aligns with traditional Japanese medicine.<ref>富士川游, 中外医事新報, 1915.</ref> * Nunakawahime's name reflects a connection to [[Echigo Province]]’s [[Kubiki District]], where the {{ill|Nunakawa Shrine|ja|奴奈川神社|qq=draft}} is dedicated to her.
